Recoding 
=========

Recoding is a code maintenance process that involves large scale changes
to a body of code. Recoding can be complex and tedious, but if done well,
can result in large, overall improvements to not possible by hacking code
on a case by case basis. If done poorly however, recoding can exacerbate
existing problems while introducing new ones.

The objective of recoding is always to IMPROVE code already in play, and
to do so CHEAPLY in terms of time and effort. In general, recode work is
much less fun than creating new code, and involves code that works well
enough for the most part anyway. There's a cost/benefit tradeoff involved
in all recodes that should be considered before a serious recode effort
is undertaken.


1 - Functional recode
---------------------

A functional recode is a bare-bones, minimalist recode that aims to
simply get the code working properly. This is really a fancy name for
general bugfixing and whatnot. Where possible (i.e. doesn't cause
compatibility problems), current coding standards should be used in a
localized way, but the goal here is not to make the code pretty or even
more maintainable. Just get it working. This approach is often taken for
complex mudlib/guild code that needs a few tweaks here and there, but
where complete recoding would be difficult. It can also be used for
areas that break due to mudlib changes.


2 - Structural recode
---------------------

A structural recode is aimed at fixing external code organization so that
it is easier to maintain. This kind of recode is most commonly performed
when moving old areas out of a wizard's personal directories. For this
kind of recode, it is sufficient to move files into the correct structure
(see wizhelp 8.7) and make sure everything works as per a functional
recode. N.B. This may include fixing things that break because they were
not very portable to begin with, and miscellaneous bugs that have been
there from before the recode - since you're in there anyway, you may as
well fix the real bugs.


3 - Full themeless recode
-------------------------

This is comprehensive recode that aims to bring all aspects of the code
in line with current code/balance/content standards. The aim is to bring
the code up to minimum spec only, not to completely redo it into
something much better than the original. This should be done periodically
to all maintained code/areas to keep them in line with current coding
standards.


4 - Complete recode
-------------------

There are no upper bounds to what this entails. Usually complete recodes
are not done on areas because it's a lot of work that's not particularly
fun, for little gain. Complete recodes of guild/mudlib code are more
common, and tend to include things like tightening up code in general,
altering aspects of theme, adding new functionality etc. This type of
recode is almost as much work as starting from scratch.


